      • canImport

        boolean canImport()
        Returns true if this T supports import. Currently, CSVOptions, XLSOptions, and XMLOptions all support import, meaning that TMS Tables can be imported from comma separated value (CSV) files, Excel files (both xls and xlsx formatsare supported), and XML documents.
        Returns:
        true if this T supports import

      • isColumnLabels

        boolean isColumnLabels()
        Returns true if this T is configured to import or export TMS Column labels.
        Returns:
        true if this T imports/export Column labels

      • withColumnLabels

        T withColumnLabels()
        Returns a new T with column labels enabled. When exporting, this means that labels assigned to the Columns in the exported Table will be included in the output. When importing, this means that column labels assigned to the data in the import file will be assigned to the Columns read from the file.
        Returns:
        a new T with column labels enabled

      • withColumnLabels

        T withColumnLabels(boolean enabled)
        Returns a new T with column labels enabled or disabled. When exporting, this means that when enabled, labels assigned to the Columns in the exported Table will be included in the output. When disabled, column labels in the exported table are ignored and are not included in the output. When importing, this means that when enabled, column labels assigned to the data in the import file will be assigned to the Columns read from the file.
        Parameters:
        enabled - true to include Column labels, false to ignore them
        Returns:
        a new T with column labels enabled or disabled

      • isRowLabels

        boolean isRowLabels()
        Returns true if this T is configured to import or export TMS Row labels.
        Returns:
        true if this T imports/export Row labels

      • withRowLabels

        T withRowLabels()
        Returns a new T with row labels enabled. When exporting, this means that labels assigned to the Rows in the exported Table will be included in the output. When importing, this means that row labels assigned to the data in the import file will be assigned to the Rows read from the file.
        Returns:
        a new T with row labels enabled

      • withRowLabels

        T withRowLabels(boolean enabled)
        Returns a new T with row labels enabled or disabled, as per the supplied parameter b. When exporting, this means that when enabled, labels assigned to the Rows in the exported Table will be included in the output. When disabled, row labels in the exported table are ignored and are not included in the output. When importing, this means that when enabled, row labels assigned to the data in the import file will be assigned to the Rows read from the file.
        Parameters:
        enabled - true to include Row labels, false to ignore them
        Returns:
        a new T with row labels enabled or disabled

      • isIgnoreEmptyRows

        boolean isIgnoreEmptyRows()
        Returns true if this T is configured to ignore empty Rows when importing/exporting TMS Tables.
        Returns:
        true if empty Rows are ignored on import/export

      • withIgnoreEmptyRows

        T withIgnoreEmptyRows()
        Returns a new T where empty rows in the imported file are ignored, and where empty Rows in a Table are ignored and not included in the export file.
        Returns:
        a new T where empty rows are ignored

      • withIgnoreEmptyRows

        T withIgnoreEmptyRows(boolean enabled)
        Sets the behavior this T uses to handle empty rows. When set to true, empty rows in the source Table are ignored (not written to the output file). On import, empty rows in the source file are ignored. When set to false, empty rows are included in the exported file, in a file-format-appropriate manner. On import, empty Rows are inserted into the new Table when encountered in the imported file.
        Parameters:
        enabled - true to import/export empty Rows, false to ignore them
        Returns:
        a new T where empty rows are or are not ignored

      • isIgnoreEmptyColumns

        boolean isIgnoreEmptyColumns()
        Returns true if this T is configured to ignore empty Columns when importing/exporting TMS Tables.
        Returns:
        true if empty Columns are ignored on import/export

      • withIgnoreEmptyColumns

        T withIgnoreEmptyColumns()
        Returns a new T where empty columns in the imported file are ignored, and where empty Columns in a Table are ignored and not included in the export file.
        Returns:
        a new T where empty columns are ignored

      • withIgnoreEmptyColumns

        T withIgnoreEmptyColumns(boolean enabled)
        Sets the behavior this T uses to handle empty columns. When set to true, empty columns in the source Table are ignored (not written to the output file). On import, empty columns in the source file are ignored. When set to false, empty columns are included in the exported file, in a file-format-appropriate manner. On import, empty Columns are inserted into the new Table when encountered in the imported file.
        Parameters:
        enabled - true to import/export empty Columns, false to ignore them
        Returns:
        a new T where empty columns are or are not ignored
